Yes, creating a custom class to combine an integer and a string is a great approach. This will help you manage related data more efficiently. Below is a step-by-step guide to implementing this.

### Step 1: Create a Custom Class

Create a new Java class named `Item.java`:

```java
public class Item {
    private int number;
    private String text;

    public Item(int number, String text) {
        this.number = number;
        this.text = text;
    }

    public int getNumber() {
        return number;
    }

    public String getText() {
        return text;
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        return "Number: " + number + ", Text: " + text;
    }
}
```

### Step 2: Modify MainActivity to Use the Custom Class

Now, modify `MainActivity.java` to use the `Item` class. Here’s the updated code:

```java
import android.os.Bundle;
import android.view.View;
import android.widget.ArrayAdapter;
import android.widget.Button;
import android.widget.ListView;
import androidx.appcompat.app.AppCompatActivity;
import java.util.ArrayList;

public class MainActivity extends AppCompatActivity {

    private ListView listView;
    private Button addButton;
    private ArrayList<Item> itemList = new ArrayList<>();

    @Override
    protected void onCreate(Bundle savedInstanceState) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState);
        setContentView(R.layout.activity_main);

        listView = findViewById(R.id.list_view);
        addButton = findViewById(R.id.add_button);

        // Set up ArrayAdapter for the ListView with the custom Item class
        final ArrayAdapter<Item> adapter = new ArrayAdapter<Item>(this, android.R.layout.simple_list_item_1, itemList);
        listView.setAdapter(adapter);

        addButton.setOnClickListener(new View.OnClickListener() {
            @Override
            public void onClick(View v) {
                int number = itemList.size() + 1;
                String text = "Item " + number;
                itemList.add(new Item(number, text));
                adapter.notifyDataSetChanged();
            }
        });
    }
}
```

### Step 3: Update Layout if Needed

You can keep the layout unchanged, as the data binding will now happen through the `Item` class's `toString()` method.

### Explanation

1. **Custom Class (`Item`)**: This class holds an integer and a string, with getter methods and a `toString()` method to format how the items will be displayed in the ListView.

2. **Single ArrayList**: We maintain just one `ArrayList<Item>` which stores both integers and strings together.

3. **Adapter**: The `ArrayAdapter` now uses `Item` objects, and the `toString()` method of the `Item` class determines how they appear in the ListView.

### Summary

This approach not only simplifies the data structure but also makes it easier to manage related attributes together. You'll now have a more organized way of displaying data in your ListView. When you run this code, clicking the button will add items with both an integer and string to the list.

